 a quest (with two possible ways to finish it, one requires killing the bear, the other allows a means to not kill the bear) This NPC is a worshipper of Tunare. <br>
<br>
Why would a spell be allowed to exsist if it wasnt to be used? Charm Animal (which WILL agro the beast when worn off), Fear animal, are just two examples.<br>
<br>
Twotribes, the character, does NOT see an absolute ban on killing animals. Such is not the will of Tunare, rather the desire of the followers in a portion of Norrath.<br>
<br>
As for Woodelf and High Elf followers.... Humm, as I recall , one quest from the Paladin Hall in Felewith has the Paladins (or others) hunting wolves for their skin. And Some of the guilds in Kelethin also request you kill animals (wolves usually).<br>
<br>
But that isnt the point. If you want to role play not killing certain animals, go ahead.... you decide what your character does. I am simply showing that it isnt a &quot;requirement&quot; of Tunare to not kill said beasts. And one COULD create all kinds of &quot;proof&quot; within the frame work of the game to support either idea.<br>
<br>
IF you believe the death of wolves and Bears is bad, and wont hunt them...... Doesnt that make paying someone else (be it vendor or player) an act of ENCOURAGING the slaughter of said animals? Just a possible thought one could use to try to dissuade someone from either killing wolves or to be used to dissuade the practice of making armor from their pelts.<br>
<br>
There are many many shades of how one can roleplay the concept of killing or not killing wolves and bears, I simply remind you that they arent the ONLY creations of Tunare (though if you want to roleplay it is, go ahead, just dont get upset if someone tries to convince you otherwise)<br>
<br>
No I am not trying to tell anyone how to roleplay. I am simply providing information that may be used to help someone make a decision (if they wanted or needed info).<br>
<br>
Back when EQ first started I had several heated discussions with people that tried to claim that roleplaying a druid (and Ranger)MEANT not killing animals, they used that arguement to try and prove that you couldnt roleplay in EQ. <br>
<br>
The only absolutes are the game engine and a persons self imposed ones. And both can and do change over time.<br>
<br>
So , to repeat. All this is MY interpretation, based on things I chose to believe. Each person has to decide their own path. And unless your path leads to harassing other players, it is a valid path. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/urobingoodfellow.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Robin Goodfellow</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 149<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/30/02 11:12:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1225.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Tailoring AND staying in character</span><hr size=1> Twotribes:<br>
<br>
Don't get me wrong.  I believe that Nature is as bloodthirsty ('Red in tooth and claw&quot;, as Tennyson wrote) as it is tranquil.  Balance in all things.<br>
<br>
I think those who think druids should not kill any animals are deluded.  But I only attack animals in self-defense, or those animals that would attack me (i.e., primarily cats).<br>
<br>
I don't often buy wolf pelts or bear pelts.  I do for my own armor, but I don't make small sizes for anyone else unless they provide their own pelt (and I don't speak human well enough to sell large sizes to anyone).  Actually, for the studded I wear personally, I traded a bunch of cat pelts for a bunch of wolf pelts of the same quality with someone.<br>
<br>
I certainly don't think these strictures apply necessarily to every worshiper of Tunare, and certainly, any being has a right to defend itself from attack.  That's survival of the fittest, which should be one of the prime tenets any follower of Tunare follows.<br>
<br>
Lasgalen<br>
